00:37:57,340 --> 00:37:59,480
Because it feels like a devastating critique.

562
00:37:59,480 --> 00:38:01,580
It is a structural teardown.

563
00:38:02,160 --> 00:38:06,280
SpherePop exposes what we might call the hollow core of large language models.

564
00:38:06,800 --> 00:38:11,540
To understand the critique, you have to look at how an LLM actually functions under the hood.

565
00:38:11,900 --> 00:38:13,620
It is an autoregressive engine.

566
00:38:13,740 --> 00:38:16,100
Meaning it predicts the next word.

567
00:38:16,260 --> 00:38:16,500
Right.

568
00:38:16,800 --> 00:38:21,580
It looks at the prompt you give it, the context window, and it rapidly calculates a massive

569
00:38:21,580 --> 00:38:27,500
probability distribution over its entire vocabulary to determine what the absolute most likely

570
00:38:27,500 --> 00:38:30,100
next token or word fragment should be.

571
00:38:30,680 --> 00:38:33,860
Then it samples from that distribution to output a word.

572
00:38:34,280 --> 00:38:38,300
It's the world's most sophisticated, multidimensional autocomplete.

573
00:38:38,720 --> 00:38:40,560
It's just guessing the next word.

574
00:38:41,000 --> 00:38:41,320
Yes.

575
00:38:41,320 --> 00:38:48,180
But the fatal flaw, viewed through the lens of SpherePop, is that the LLM maintains maximal

