00:38:56,240 --> 00:38:58,920
They can click Regenerate Response.

579
00:38:59,600 --> 00:39:05,660
They can slightly tweak the temperature parameter, which controls randomness, and run the exact

580
00:39:05,660 --> 00:39:08,600
same prompt again to get a totally different outplay.

581
00:39:08,920 --> 00:39:10,660
Because it hasn't actually committed to anything.

582
00:39:10,840 --> 00:39:11,400
Exactly.

583
00:39:12,240 --> 00:39:18,720
The LLM's internal foundational structure, its core weights and biases, are never permanently,

584
00:39:19,180 --> 00:39:22,840
causally altered by the text it generates in a chat window.

585
00:39:22,840 --> 00:39:25,840
Because the chat window is just a temporary sandbox.

586
00:39:26,320 --> 00:39:32,000
The model isn't learning from the conversation in real time in a way that permanently overwrites

587
00:39:32,000 --> 00:39:32,980
its core identity.

588
00:39:33,180 --> 00:39:33,340
Yeah.

589
00:39:33,400 --> 00:39:39,440
So because they can always hit backspace, because their past isn't fixed into a rigid, immutable

590
00:39:39,440 --> 00:39:43,120
chain, they aren't really doing anything.

591
00:39:43,120 --> 00:39:43,760
Correct.

592
00:39:44,300 --> 00:39:51,880
From a rigorous SpherePop perspective, LLMs simulate action, but they do not act.

593
00:39:52,740 --> 00:39:59,300
Action, true agency, requires a permanent, irreversible pruning of the option space.

594
00:39:59,740 --> 00:40:01,560
It requires popping a bubble.

595
00:40:01,560 --> 00:40:08,900
When an LLM outputs a highly definitive declarative statement, like, I believe X is definitively

